Ontology Specification Draft

Abstract

The STORM (STOrytelling and Metaphors) ontology examines metaphors and their connections to storytelling theories by influential scholars. More specifically, the ontology focuses on metaphors found in Shakespearean works and the ways in which they reflect the universality of narrative structure, as anticipated in theories of narratology. With this project we attempt to demonstrate that metaphors do not only shed light on universal narrative elements, but that they may also provide insight into the main ideas of a story.

greimas' theoryc back to ToC or Class ToC

IRI: https://github.com/stormOntology/stormOntology.github.io/blob/master/storm#Greimas'_theory

Greimas' work on semiotics and narratology make him one of the most important scholars in the field, with theories on the structure of a story and character archetypes. His work allowed us to search for and draw connections between structure and metaphors, with the latter reflecting important events of each narrative stage, bringing forth the motivations and aims of the main characters and adding to the semantic redundancy of the dominant themes of the story.
has super-classes
storytelling aspect c
has sub-classes
initial lack c, isotopy c, narrative program c, polemical structure c, value c
